The Cinderteeth Mountains are a discontinuous volcanic arc running west to northeast, named for the jaw-like ridgeline silhouette visible from eastern lowlands at dawn. The indigenous name is Thrak-Essen (Judgment-Spine or Breathing Spine) in the extinct Ridgekin highland dialect. The range is tectonically coupled to a deep continental fault; seismic events far from the mountains can trigger sympathetic tremors. Six operational subregions: the Ember Crown (active caldera peaks), the Bellspine (fracture-scarred mid-ridge with acoustic hazards), the Chalkwind Saddles (primary commercial transit corridor), the Glasswash Fans (lahar-hardened volcanic glass plains), the Blackstep Footholds (mixed forest-volcanic foothills), and the Western Fold (site of the Spirebound Conclave sanctum). The Ventspeakers, the pre-civilizational highland inhabitants, maintained oracular relationships with specific vents and left polished name-stones at vent mouths throughout the range. The Spirebound Conclave built their sanctum in the Western Fold and embedded resonance crystals at fault intersections along the Bellspine; when the Conclave collapsed, these crystals were never retrieved. The Ashfall Monsoon — volcanic outgassing from a major eruptive episode — devastated Kowloon's delta and caused mass displacement of Ashborn populations. Commercial outputs: obsidian, sulfur, pumice, ferric scoria. The Ash Cult treats the mountains as a theological instrument, reading eruptions as civic verdicts.

