Serathi aerial perspective on the Cinderteeth identifies the range's most important operational feature: ash column behavior determines sky-road safety across a far larger area than the mountain's ground footprint suggests.
During high-activity periods, ash columns from the Ember Crown develop static charge and produce irregular lightning ground-strikes in a two-to-four-mile radius; the column drifts on upper-level wind patterns that differ significantly from ground-level winds, so the strike zone moves unpredictably.
Serathi sky-road corridors crossing the continental interior are re-routed during Crown activity, adding transit time to any east-west crossing north of Roc Road.
From altitude, the Bellspine's tooth-ridge separation is clearly visible as the jaw profile that gave the caravan-era name. The Ember Crown glow-vents are visible at night from considerable distance — a navigation reference that functions precisely because the range is dangerous.
Rakuen-based Serathi maintain informal observation logs of Crown glow patterns as a local sky-condition indicator; these logs are more current than any city's official seismic monitoring.
